				\begin{document}$$ \nabla\cdot\mathbf{j}_\parallel= - \nabla\cdot\mathbf{j}_\perp= -\nabla \cdot\biggl( \frac{\mathbf{B}}{B^2} \times\rho\frac{d\mathbf{u}}{dt} + \frac{\mathbf{B}}{B^2} \times\nabla P\biggr). $$\end{document} Equation (3) can be integrated to yield (e.g., Vasyliunas 1970) 4\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \frac{j_\parallel}{B} = -\int_0^s \nabla\cdot \biggl( \frac{\mathbf{B}}{B^2} \times\rho\frac{d\mathbf{u}}{dt} + \frac{\mathbf{B}}{B^2} \times \nabla P\biggr)\frac{ds}{B}, $$\end{document} where the integral is taken along a field line from a point where j∥ vanishes (say, the neutral sheet) to a point of interest such as the ionosphere. The first term on the RHS of (4) is termed the ‘inertial current’, and is non-zero only during acceleration or deceleration of the flows. We note here that ‘inertia-driven’ currents associated with the braking might have the sense of region-1 (Shiokawa et al. 1998), but are found to play only a minor role in comparison to ‘pressure-driven’ currents, represented by the second term on the RHS of (4) (Birn et al. 1999).

